== Appendix 1: Other City-based commons experiences and projects ==

=== Barcelona ===

After the major social mobilizations of 2011 and the election of a commons-oriented coalition, the city of Barcelona has created new urban institutions to support the development of a commons-orientated economy. This entails the collaboration with a knowledge coalition of experts with a focus on the commons (BarCola29), new communication platforms (Procomuns) as well as experiments with in-depth forms of citizen participation (Decidim.barcelona). The city has created an open source Municipal Action Plan which relates to the local commons-based collaborative economy, specifically recognizing it and supporting it with an ambitious investment plan (Impetus Plan30). More about Barcelona’s policies below:
* In 2000, Barcelona became the first European city to implement a Solar Thermal Ordinance (STO), making it compulsory to use solar energy to supply 60 percent of running hot water in all new buildings, renovated buildings, and buildings changing their use (Source: [[Solar Thermal Ordinance]])
* Policy Plan: A government measure for open digitisation: free software and agile development of public administration services. The Open Digitisation Programme from Barcelona City Council’s Office for Technology and Digital Innovation. https://ajuntament.barcelona.cat/digital/sites/default/files/LE_MesuradeGovern_EN_9en.pdf
* The “Barcelona City Data Commons” initiative raises the question of how we can make the most out of data by putting the digital right of the citizen at the core; [[Barcelona City Data Commons]]
* Barcelona Activa, the new department inside the local development agency, aims to encourage alternative economies
* the Barcelona Commissioner for Cooperative, Social and Solidarity Economy and Consumption is relegated with the task of promoting and visualising the social and solidarity in order to create new commons-oriented policy directions  in the City Council;
* The Impetus Plan for the Social and Solidarity Economy in Barcelona, [[Impetus Plan for the Social and Solidarity Economy in Barcelona]]
* Barcelona Initiative for Technological Sovereignty: BITS: Activists, Academics & Universities promoting technological sovereignty, [[Barcelona Initiative for Technological Sovereignty]]

=== Lille ===

The Assemblée des Communs in Lille has been active since 2015, and actively gives a voice to the social philosophy of the city as a commons. It is similar in many ways to Procumuns.net in Barcelona, but has a much more permanent operation and more in-depth proposals for institutional adaptation. This example gives us insight into possible autonomous institutions that are supported by civil society and commons-orientated citizen initiatives.<br />
Source: https://wiki.lescommuns.org/wiki/48h_de_la_contribution/Charte_des_pratiques

=== Frome and Saillans ===

The British town of Frome, as well as Saillans in France, are examples of more radical political experiences, as citizens’ initiatives have created political coalitions (Independents for Frome31) that have almost entirely replaced traditional political parties. The Frome model is called ‘Flatpack Democracy’, based on the ideas of Peter Macfadyen.
Saillans, http://www.mairiedesaillans26.fr/gouvernance-collegiale-et-participative/
Frome, [[Flatpack Democracy Civic Politics Revolution in Frome]]
(Bauwens & Onzia, 2017)

=== Milan and Naples ===

Milan has oriented towards embedding startups in the communities through collaborative spaces, i.e. the ‘sharing city policy strategy’. This Milan Pact particularly encourages direct participation between civil society and small producers across Food Policy Councils
Sources:
[[Milan's Sharing City Policy Strategy]] http://www.fian.be/IMG/pdf/conseils_politique_alimentaire_uk_web.pdf


Similarly, Naples has a special position, Commissioner for the commons, and is more friendly to turning temporary occupations into recognized commons. As such it represents a more radical model than the more consensual model represented by the Bologna Regulation
Sources:
[[Naples' Government Resolution no. 446 - 2016 on the Identification of Urban Spaces as Commons]] ; [[Naples Council Resolution of 2016 on Occupied Buildings as Common Goods]]

=== Cleveland / Preston ===

The Evergreen Cooperative model of Cleveland, Ohio aims to use the purchasing power of ‘anchor institutions’ such as hospitals and universities, to create a thriving local economy based on local cooperatives in the disadvantaged inner city. The initiative has been successful in already creating a number of them in food and laundry services. (See Co-Cities Report on the Urban Commons Transitions [[Co-Cities Report on the Urban Commons Transitions]]; Cleveland model https://community-wealth.org/content/cleveland-model-how-evergreen-cooperatives-are-building-community-wealth )

The Cleveland model was adapted in the UK by the City of Preston. The Preston model however is also focused on alternative forms of ownership that both enrich livelihoods of residents and workers, as well as give them opportunities to actively participate in economic decisions that affect them and the future of their city. Even prior to working with anchor institutions, the Preston council had backed plans to develop cooperatives and a public financial institution.

=== Commons transition plan in Amsterdam ===

After the creation of a progressive coalition, Amsterdam city officials looked toward transformative policies and mechanisms in support of commons. The city hired the Commons Network as consultant to set in motion a study of local urban commons, with a vision to expand them. A city official is in charge of coordination. It would seem that the Covid-19 induced financial retraction has endangered this project. See the following brochure for a cartography of commons-oriented projects in Amsterdam. A commons transition plan for Amsterdam is being developed currently. Other initiatives instigated by the progressive coalition include the Fearless Cities project, after the municipal victory of the En Comu coalition in Barcelona. This project is relatively well funded. The second, the ‘maak’ accord was meant to create funding for contributory logics, ie. to strengthen already existing citizen initiatives that solve societal issues; this project is also said to be in danger due to the Covid-19 austerity. The original aim was to secure from 2 to 10% of the city budget.

=== Amsterdam Doughnut Economics Action Lab (updating) ===

Amsterdam City has decided to integrate the Doughnut framing as proposed by Kate Raworth with its circular economy urban transition strategy. Several cities around Europe and elsewhere have expressed interest in integrating the doughnut framework into their policies, a process which includes creating city doughnut portraits (See
https://www.kateraworth.com/2020/04/08/amsterdam-city-doughnut/; https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/08/amsterdam-doughnut-model-mend-post-coronavirus-economy ), a methodology which they have made open access since the very beginning (See
https://www.kateraworth.com/2020/07/16/so-you-want-to-create-a-city-doughnut/ )

=== Sydney Commons Transition Plan ===

Sydney Commons Lab’s (SCL) ‘Sydney Commons Transition Plan’ as one possible path toward social and institutional change looks beyond neoclassical market economy, promoting the study and support of changes that empower residents and communities and incentivise innovative sustainability and commons-oriented projects. In the plan, benefits for the City of Sydney are identified under three main headings:
# Social – neighbourhood and community cohesion, inclusion and connection; improving community skills and confidence; developing community resilience and autonomy; turning passive ‘consumers’ into ‘contributors’;
# Environmental – sharing and maximising utility of resources and food; developing community level ‘stewardship’ norms for managing resources and associated environmental benefit;
# Economic – local economy benefits (new regenerative business models and approaches to creating meaningful livelihoods); economic resilience; peer-to-peer arrangements for reduced-cost goods and services.
See [[Commons Transition Plan for the City of Sydney]]<br />
Report: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1TxN4-XFORuS6i_xgL0QhLyWODXXWS6zx/view
[[Sydney Commons Lab]]

=== The City of Antwerp as a Commons ===

Commons Lab '''Antwerp''' is a grassroots, not for profit organization, founded at the beginning of 2018 (by Koen Wijnants et a.)  in the city of Antwerp, Belgium. It is an experimental City Lab investigating the theory and practice of 'Antwerp as a commons', connecting active citizens with social innovators and key local stakeholders interested in creating a more sustainable, democratic and just city. Their activities involve mapping (identifying, inventorizing, analyzing) commoning activities in Antwerp, a civic media strategy around the idea of ‘the city as a commons’, experimental Commons Assemblies (e.g. Antwerp garden city, Antwerp bike city), collective visioning, tool development for practitioners and the creation of an Antwerp commons transition plan.<br />
For more, see https://www.commonslabantwerpen.org/.


